    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>findByInventoryIdIn(List&lt;Long&gt; inventoryIdList)</code> should do the trick.</p>\n<p>The HTTP request parameter format would be like so:</p>\n<pre><code>Yes ?id=1,2,3\nNo  ?id=1&amp;id=2&amp;id=3\n</code></pre>\n<p>The complete list of JPA repository keywords can be found in the <a href=\"http://docs.spring.io/spring-data/jpa/docs/current/reference/html/#repository-query-keywords\" rel=\"noreferrer\">current documentation listing</a>. It shows that <code>IsIn</code> is equivalent – if you prefer the verb for readability – and that JPA also supports <code>NotIn</code> and <code>IsNotIn</code>.</p>\n<p>If <code>inventoryId</code> has the primary key, you can simply use <code>yourRepo.findAll(inventoryIdList)</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
